===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|civil law|transitive}} To transfer the [[title]] of from one to another; to [[alienate]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1861|author=Anne Manning|title=The chronicle of Ethelfled|page=153|passage=Thereat the holy mother took grief; for, if I died before my profession, what would become of the goodly hereditaments that were to be '''abalienated''' to the monastery.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1994|journal=Yugoslav law|page=46|passage=In addition, compelling to sell was not necessary either, because the foreigner, led by economic logic and his own interests, would try hard to '''abalienate''' the objects and means of work which are not used in production or in some other type of {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[estrange]]; to cause [[alienation]] of.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1698|title=A voyage to the East-Indies|page=43|passage={{...}} serves for nothing else than to '''abalienate''' the Infidels from the ''Christian'' Church.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1883|title=A commentary on the Greek text of the Epistle of Paul to the Ephesians|page=165|passage=National distinction did not, indeed, exist in patriarchal times, but by the formation of the theocracy the other races of men were formally '''abalienated''' from Israel, and no doubt their own vices and idolatry justified their exclusion.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Edwin Sandys|title=The sermons of Edwin Sandys|year=1841|volume=4|page=300|passage=The devil and his deceitful angels do so bewitch them, and fill their hearts with vain cogitations, so '''abalienate''' their minds, and trouble their memory, that they cannot tell what is said: it is forgotten by that it is spoken.}}

